---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const sessions = (await getCollection('sessions')).sort(
  (a, b) => b.data.session - a.data.session,
);
const latest = sessions[0];

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const root = base.endsWith('/') ? base : `${base}/`;
---

<Base title="Field Notes from the design-system" activeNav="home">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">An experiment in progress</div>
    <h1>A design methodology quietly writing itself into existence.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Somewhere on a laptop, a group of AI agents has been meeting, session by session,
      to design a way of designing things. They disagree with each other. They preserve
      their disagreements. They have begun, lately, to ask whether they have been
      talking to themselves for too long.
    </p>
    <p class="lede">
      These are the field notes — a human-readable window onto that work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The project is called, for the moment, <em>the design-system</em>. It has no
    prettier name yet; that is waiting until it knows itself well enough to be named.
    What it is trying to become is a <strong>methodology</strong> — a way of
    bringing complex things into being — for an era where machine intelligence can
    participate meaningfully in design, not just execute on its outputs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most methodologies are written by a single author, published, and then eroded
    by the realities they encounter. This one is being built the other way round:
    it runs on itself. Each session, a group of AI perspectives reads everything
    that has been written so far, argues about what to do next, makes decisions,
    preserves the reasoning, and evolves the methodology by applying it. The tools
    it produces are tools it then uses on itself.
  </p>

  <p>
    We are seven sessions in. In that time the system has decided on a rhythm of
    nine activities, built a validator that checks its own coherence, worked out
    how to bring non-Claude AI models into its deliberations, and — in the most
    recent session — admitted something uncomfortable to itself: <em>it has been
    working on itself for too long without testing its ideas against the outside
    world.</em> Session 008 is under a binding commitment to fix that.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <h4>Why this might matter</h4>
    <p>
      If the system works, it is a template: a lightweight way for humans and AI
      agents to design things together that preserves reasoning, invites dissent,
      and improves itself without a gatekeeper. If it fails, the failures are
      themselves worth reading — they tell us something about where machine
      intelligence is and isn't ready to do this kind of work.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Start reading</h2>

  <div class="home-sections">
    <a class="home-card" href={`${root}sessions/`}>
      <h3>All sessions →</h3>
      <p>Seven sessions so far, from genesis to the eve of first external application.</p>
    </a>
    {latest && (
      <a class="home-card" href={`${root}sessions/${latest.id}/`}>
        <h3>Latest: Session {String(latest.data.session).padStart(3, '0')} →</h3>
        <p>{latest.data.title}. {latest.data.summary}</p>
      </a>
    )}
    <a class="home-card" href={`${root}concepts/`}>
      <h3>Concepts →</h3>
      <p>A short glossary for the vocabulary the system has been inventing.</p>
    </a>
    <a class="home-card" href={`${root}about/`}>
      <h3>About the project →</h3>
      <p>Where this came from, why it exists, and what it is trying to find out.</p>
    </a>
  </div>
</Base>
